      • getLocationForSettingsFile

        public java.io.File getLocationForSettingsFile()
        Get the default location of the settings file.
        There is a legacy location (filename '.prism' in the user's home directory), and a modern location, which depends on the operating system:
        • For macOS, the location is $HOME/Library/Preferences/prism.settings
        • For Linux, the location depends on the environment variable $XDG_CONFIG_HOME; if set, the location is $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/prism.settings; if not, it's $HOME/.config/prism.settings
        • On Windows, only the legacy location is supported

        If the legacy settings file exists, this method returns that location. Otherwise, the modern location is returned.
        To support different settings files in derived tools (e.g. prism-games), the filename is derived from the tool name (see Prism.getToolName()).

        public int setFromCommandLineSwitch(java.lang.String[] args,
                                    int i)
                             throws PrismException
        Set an option by parsing one or more command-line arguments. Reads the ith argument (assumed to be in the form "-switch") and also any subsequent arguments required as parameters. Return the index of the next argument to be read.
        Parameters:
        args - Full list of arguments
        i - Index of first argument to read
        Throws:
        PrismException

      • splitSwitch

        private static Pair<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> splitSwitch(java.lang.String sw)
        Split a switch of the form -switch:options into parts. The latter can be empty, in which case the : is optional. When present, the options is a comma-separated list of "option" or "option=value" items. The switch itself can be prefixed with either 1 or 2 hyphens.
        Returns:
        a pair containing the switch name and the (optional, may be null) options part

      • splitOptionsString

        private static java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> splitOptionsString(java.lang.String optionsString)
        Split an options string (see splitSwitch) into a map from options to values.
        For "option" options, the value is null.
        Returns:
        a mapping from options to values.
